WEBVTT

1
00:00:11.010 --> 00:00:11.845
[Claire] <i>Previously...</i>

2
00:00:11.928 --> 00:00:13.346
You don't intend to live your life

3
00:00:13.430 --> 00:00:15.932
in order to please
other people's expectations.

4
00:00:16.015 --> 00:00:17.600
May I call you by your Christian name?

5
00:00:17.684 --> 00:00:20.895
Why. yes. It's Elspeth.

6
00:00:20.979 --> 00:00:22.188
And I'm Claire.

7
00:00:22.272 --> 00:00:25.316
All I'm asking is that
you contact this Claudel fellow.

8
00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:26.484
encourage him to meet me.

9
00:00:26.568 --> 00:00:27.736
I'll consider it.

10
00:00:27.819 --> 00:00:29.446
You think Frank is torturing you?

11
00:00:29.529 --> 00:00:32.157
I just don't know
what's real or not anymore.

12
00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:33.283
Rob Cameron.

13
00:00:33.366 --> 00:00:35.452
He read my date for time-travel
by accident.

14
00:00:35.535 --> 00:00:38.455
No one on the Ridge kens
of this gold's existence.

15
00:00:38.538 --> 00:00:39.539
Canna let them find out.

16
00:00:39.622 --> 00:00:42.250
Daddy's book warns of a battle
coming to the backcountry.

17
00:00:42.333 --> 00:00:44.461
We'll need a lot more
than just a few hunting rifles.

18
00:00:44.544 --> 00:00:46.254
And Savannah is the place to get them.

19
00:00:46.337 --> 00:00:49.591
Lord John Grey included a letter
of safe passage with his invitation.

20
00:00:49.674 --> 00:00:52.093
You are raising
a Loyalist Militia on my land.

21
00:00:52.177 --> 00:00:53.011
I am.

22
00:00:53.094 --> 00:00:55.972
You are mistaken
if you think I will allow it.

23
00:00:59.559 --> 00:01:02.270
I have reconsidered your plan
to get guns to arm the Ridge.

24
00:01:02.353 --> 00:01:03.938
It'll still be dangerous.

25
00:01:04.022 --> 00:01:06.816
Randall's book says the battle to end
the siege of Savannah

26
00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:08.485
will be on the 9th of October.

27
00:01:09.402 --> 00:01:10.737
Continentals'll fail.

28
00:01:11.237 --> 00:01:14.741
battle'll be bloody. but it willna reach
the center of the city.

29
00:01:14.824 --> 00:01:17.035
so if you wait out the fighting.
you should be safe.

30
00:01:17.118 --> 00:01:18.453
As will Fergus. Marsali.

31
00:01:19.245 --> 00:01:21.664
And the children can stay here with us.
of course.

32
00:01:22.665 --> 00:01:25.543
Take this to Lieutenant Colonel
Francis Marion.

33
00:01:25.627 --> 00:01:29.130
Book says he'll be with
the Continental Army in Savannah.

34
00:01:29.631 --> 00:01:31.841
Has a great deal
of experience with militias.

35
00:01:31.925 --> 00:01:34.344
Might be keen to arm men
from the backcountry.

36
00:01:34.427 --> 00:01:36.095
So. we're starting our own militia?

37
00:01:36.179 --> 00:01:41.017
It's that. or we join Benjamin Cleveland
and his Overmountain men.

38
00:01:41.768 --> 00:01:45.772
I'll be damned if I'll report back
to that murderin' bastard.

39
00:01:45.855 --> 00:01:49.108
You think it'd at least have
the decency to shine. like in a film.

40
00:01:55.949 --> 00:01:57.117
What about bandits?

41
00:01:57.200 --> 00:02:00.411
Do you want to make it into musket balls
like you did the last time?

42
00:02:00.495 --> 00:02:02.455
No. there's no time.

43
00:02:02.539 --> 00:02:04.124
But I do have an idea.

44
00:02:12.924 --> 00:02:15.510
<i>♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

45
00:02:15.593 --> 00:02:19.889
<i>♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪</i>

46
00:02:19.973 --> 00:02:23.268
<i>♪ Say. could that lass ♪</i>

47
00:02:23.351 --> 00:02:26.396
{\an8}<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

48
00:02:28.648 --> 00:02:31.192
{\an8}<i>♪ Merry of soul ♪</i>

49
00:02:31.276 --> 00:02:35.155
{\an8}<i>♪ She sailed on a day ♪</i>

50
00:02:35.238 --> 00:02:38.241
{\an8}<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

51
00:02:38.324 --> 00:02:40.034
{\an8}<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

52
00:02:43.121 --> 00:02:46.082
{\an8}<i>♪ Billow and breeze ♪</i>

53
00:02:46.166 --> 00:02:49.085
{\an8}<i>♪ Islands and seas ♪</i>

54
00:02:49.169 --> 00:02:53.381
{\an8}<i>♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪</i>

55
00:02:55.258 --> 00:02:58.094
{\an8}<i>♪ All that was good ♪</i>

56
00:02:58.177 --> 00:03:01.139
{\an8}<i>♪ All that was fair ♪</i>

57
00:03:01.222 --> 00:03:03.933
<i>♪ All that was me ♪</i>

58
00:03:04.017 --> 00:03:05.351
{\an8}<i>♪ Is gone ♪</i>

59
00:03:10.148 --> 00:03:12.483
<i>♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

60
00:03:12.567 --> 00:03:15.653
{\an8}<i>♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪</i>

61
00:03:15.737 --> 00:03:18.489
{\an8}<i>♪ Say. could that lass ♪</i>

62
00:03:18.573 --> 00:03:20.199
{\an8}<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

63
00:03:21.826 --> 00:03:24.454
<i>♪ Merry of soul ♪</i>

64
00:03:24.537 --> 00:03:27.957
{\an8}<i>♪ She sailed on a day ♪</i>

65
00:03:28.041 --> 00:03:33.963
{\an8}<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

66
00:03:36.215 --> 00:03:41.512
{\an8}<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

67
00:04:15.588 --> 00:04:17.674
[Marsali] What's that abominable smell?

68
00:04:17.757 --> 00:04:20.885
It's a wee gift from Jamie
and Claire. It's sauerkraut.

69
00:04:21.594 --> 00:04:22.679
Ugh!

70
00:04:24.347 --> 00:04:25.348
[coughing]

71
00:04:34.941 --> 00:04:36.150
- Oh. [chuckles]
- [Marsali] Mmm.

72
00:04:36.609 --> 00:04:37.819
[laughing]

73
00:04:38.152 --> 00:04:39.070
[speaking French]

74
00:04:40.113 --> 00:04:41.197
[in English] The whiskey.

75
00:04:41.281 --> 00:04:42.323
Not the stench.

76
00:04:42.407 --> 00:04:43.533
It's Da's idea.

77
00:04:44.033 --> 00:04:45.326
Perfect hiding place.

78
00:04:45.410 --> 00:04:46.828
Thank you.

79
00:04:51.499 --> 00:04:52.500
[Marsali] Gold.

80
00:04:52.583 --> 00:04:53.793
[Roger] It's for muskets.

81
00:04:53.876 --> 00:04:55.586
Jamie's forming a militia.

82
00:04:55.670 --> 00:04:57.922
And as an officer in the Continental Camp.

83
00:04:58.006 --> 00:05:02.885
Francis Marion has been known
to arm backcountry Patriots.

84
00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:08.433
We thought it best to leave this
minor detail out of our letter to you.

85
00:05:08.516 --> 00:05:11.352
I don't imagine you intend
to traipse into an army camp

86
00:05:11.436 --> 00:05:13.146
with a king's ransom in bullion?

87
00:05:14.022 --> 00:05:17.608
No. I don't want to invite any trouble.

88
00:05:18.735 --> 00:05:21.446
Nor do I expect Marion
will have crates of guns

89
00:05:21.529 --> 00:05:24.907
just lying around the camp
that he can readily part with.

90
00:05:24.991 --> 00:05:27.201
Arrangements will have to be made.

91
00:05:27.285 --> 00:05:30.955
- So we were hoping you could...
- Aye.

92
00:05:31.039 --> 00:05:32.665
Course you can leave the gold with us.

93
00:05:32.749 --> 00:05:35.501
- Fergus has got plenty o' hiding places.
- Yeah.

94
00:05:35.585 --> 00:05:38.129
I wouldn't be surprised
if you found the Crown jewels.

95
00:05:38.212 --> 00:05:40.590
- Shouldn't be for long.
- It's no trouble.

96
00:05:40.673 --> 00:05:42.800
Now can we please
seal these barrels tightly

97
00:05:42.884 --> 00:05:45.470
until I find some Germans
who will eat this?

98
00:05:45.553 --> 00:05:46.512
[all laughing]

99
00:05:46.596 --> 00:05:49.599
Let us secrete the gold
and drink to our reunion.

100
00:05:49.682 --> 00:05:52.727
It's been too long
since I've tasted milord's divine elixir.

101
00:05:52.810 --> 00:05:53.770
That's good.

102
00:05:58.524 --> 00:06:01.986
To be safe. do you think
you should leave for the camp now?

103
00:06:03.112 --> 00:06:04.030
Dinna fash.

104
00:06:04.781 --> 00:06:08.034
There's plenty of time to find Marion
and be back before the battle.

105
00:06:13.081 --> 00:06:15.416
A wee dram'll speed me on my way.

106
00:06:33.059 --> 00:06:34.560
Cunningham wasn't exaggerating.

107
00:06:34.644 --> 00:06:36.771
He was collecting rents.
trying to ascertain

108
00:06:36.854 --> 00:06:40.108
the loyalties of the surplus
without arousing suspicion.

109
00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:43.736
Most of the families here
are loyal to the Crown.

110
00:06:43.820 --> 00:06:47.281
and those who aren't would be reluctant
to join a militia than oppose it.

111
00:06:47.406 --> 00:06:48.241
[horse snorts]

112
00:06:48.825 --> 00:06:52.161
I canna try to recruit them
without risking it

113
00:06:52.245 --> 00:06:53.871
getting back to Cunningham.

114
00:06:54.664 --> 00:06:57.375
Surely the Ardsmuir men will fight
when it comes to it.

115
00:06:57.959 --> 00:07:01.337
Of course. and a few others.
but it will only be enough

116
00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:04.882
only to recruit men from further afield.

117
00:07:05.925 --> 00:07:09.095
I leave today with Ian and Josiah.

118
00:07:09.887 --> 00:07:13.307
They ken the outposts that are cropped up
while we're away.

119
00:07:13.391 --> 00:07:16.686
Well. you can't keep Cunningham
waiting forever.

120
00:07:16.769 --> 00:07:20.481
I mean. he's going to realize
that you've no intention of joining him.

121
00:07:21.107 --> 00:07:24.652
Wouldn't it be simpler
to just evict him and be done with it?

122
00:07:24.735 --> 00:07:26.654
If I evict him or even kill him.

123
00:07:26.737 --> 00:07:29.490
someone will replace him
or come to avenge him.

124
00:07:29.574 --> 00:07:33.661
No. it's better if I have him close
so I can keep an eye on him.

125
00:07:36.831 --> 00:07:40.543
He told me his commander
is Major Patrick Ferguson.

126
00:07:42.003 --> 00:07:44.255
Frank wrote to the man.

127
00:07:45.298 --> 00:07:49.719
He's the one that formed the Loyalist
militia that fight at King's Mountain.

128
00:07:50.553 --> 00:07:54.182
I still am not sure of Frank's motives
in writing that book.

129
00:07:54.265 --> 00:07:57.059
But what he wrote
is happening before our eyes.

130
00:07:57.143 --> 00:08:00.855
I met Cleveland. and now Cunningham
speaks of Major Ferguson.

131
00:08:00.938 --> 00:08:03.191
Well. that's not proof that you fight.

132
00:08:03.274 --> 00:08:04.484
He could be lying.

133
00:08:05.067 --> 00:08:07.778
The book says that Major Ferguson
is vicious.

134
00:08:07.862 --> 00:08:09.989
Ruthless on the battlefield and off.

135
00:08:11.157 --> 00:08:15.244
Burning the homes of Rebels
without warning. forcing their allegiance.

136
00:08:17.914 --> 00:08:22.835
I'm not certain I will fight. Claire.
but if Cunningham is forming a militia.

137
00:08:23.836 --> 00:08:27.131
we need to be ready.
regardless of the book.

138
00:08:31.511 --> 00:08:35.473
To muskets. liberty and sauerkraut.
<i>mes amis.</i>

139
00:08:35.556 --> 00:08:37.558
<i>- Slainte.</i>
- [all] <i>Slainte.</i>

140
00:08:41.312 --> 00:08:42.438
[Marsali] Mmm.

141
00:08:42.522 --> 00:08:46.526
Strange for a minister
and his wife to smuggle guns. no?

142
00:08:46.609 --> 00:08:48.778
That was Brianna's idea actually.

143
00:08:48.861 --> 00:08:51.322
The last people anyone would ever suspect.

144
00:08:51.405 --> 00:08:55.409
And once we get back to the Ridge.
well. our family has a doctor.

145
00:08:55.493 --> 00:08:57.370
soldier. a minister.

146
00:08:58.329 --> 00:09:00.039
Thought we needed an armorer.

147
00:09:00.122 --> 00:09:02.625
There's me thinking you came
all this way to visit us

148
00:09:02.708 --> 00:09:05.086
and paint a wee picture for Lord John.

149
00:09:05.169 --> 00:09:07.964
It happens I recently received a letter
from His Lordship.

150
00:09:08.047 --> 00:09:11.968
He suggested I meet with one of
his associates. Percival Beauchamp.

151
00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:15.304
- Either of you familiar with this man?
- No.

152
00:09:15.888 --> 00:09:16.847
Mmm-mmm.

153
00:09:16.931 --> 00:09:19.725
He claims to have information
that will be of great interest to me.

154
00:09:19.809 --> 00:09:22.937
But Lord John says
he can be a slippery fellow.

155
00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:26.190
I must make up my own mind
whether what he says is trustworthy.

156
00:09:26.274 --> 00:09:29.193
You know. our mother's
maiden name was Beauchamp?

157
00:09:29.277 --> 00:09:31.070
The English pronounce it "Bee-cham."

158
00:09:31.153 --> 00:09:32.280
but that's a coincidence...

159
00:09:32.446 --> 00:09:33.656
- [glass shatters]
- [screams]

160
00:09:34.407 --> 00:09:35.283
[speaking French]

161
00:09:39.745 --> 00:09:41.372
[tense music playing]

162
00:09:48.713 --> 00:09:49.714
[in English] Cowards!

163
00:10:00.182 --> 00:10:01.017
[speaking French]

164
00:10:02.101 --> 00:10:03.769
[in English] Are you two all right?

165
00:10:03.853 --> 00:10:05.980
I'm... I'm fine. Are you?

166
00:10:06.063 --> 00:10:07.982
Yeah. Didna bother to put a note
this time.

167
00:10:08.065 --> 00:10:09.442
"This time"?

168
00:10:09.525 --> 00:10:11.068
What. this has happened before?

169
00:10:11.152 --> 00:10:13.029
We've had some horrible.
threatening letters.

170
00:10:13.112 --> 00:10:15.281
Filth. Bag full of dead rats.

171
00:10:15.364 --> 00:10:16.532
Another with a serpent.

172
00:10:16.616 --> 00:10:17.825
The bastard escaped.

173
00:10:22.204 --> 00:10:23.581
[Brianna] Wait. what is going on?

174
00:10:24.248 --> 00:10:26.334
[Marsali] Now. when people
dinna like the news.

175
00:10:26.417 --> 00:10:28.252
they tend to blame the printer.

176
00:10:28.336 --> 00:10:30.546
Has someone discovered you're Patriots?

177
00:10:31.213 --> 00:10:33.758
Jamie mentioned
you've been printing for the cause.

178
00:10:33.841 --> 00:10:36.677
The culprit is as likely to be
a Patriot as not.

179
00:10:37.470 --> 00:10:39.930
While. privately. we print pamphlets
for the Rebels.

180
00:10:40.014 --> 00:10:42.099
publicly. we take a more
impartial approach.

181
00:10:42.183 --> 00:10:46.270
Yeah. in trying to not anger one side.
you end up angering both sides.

182
00:10:47.605 --> 00:10:50.691
Just the life of a news printer
in these troubled times.

183
00:11:10.086 --> 00:11:12.672
- Ye have any weapons?
- Aye.

184
00:11:13.673 --> 00:11:16.217
Just the one rifle 'twixt the three of us.

185
00:11:18.427 --> 00:11:25.393
That willna do. not in war. nor hunting
or nothing. but it doesn't matter.

186
00:11:25.476 --> 00:11:27.853
I'm expecting a shipment shortly.

187
00:11:27.937 --> 00:11:31.315
When the time comes.
you'll each have your own musket and shot.

188
00:11:34.610 --> 00:11:36.904
- We'll ride with you. Mr. Fraser.
- Excellent.

189
00:11:37.405 --> 00:11:39.240
Josiah'll take down your names.

190
00:11:39.323 --> 00:11:41.033
- What's your surname?
- Miller.

191
00:11:43.327 --> 00:11:44.328
[Ian] Uncle.

192
00:11:45.830 --> 00:11:46.831
What is it. lad?

193
00:11:48.457 --> 00:11:49.583
Maybe it's nothing.

194
00:11:50.251 --> 00:11:52.044
I've recruited three more men.

195
00:11:53.087 --> 00:11:56.549
There's this Scottish fellow over yonder.

196
00:11:56.632 --> 00:11:58.717
And when he heard I was
from Fraser's Ridge.

197
00:11:58.801 --> 00:12:01.095
he mentioned he was heading there himself.

198
00:12:01.637 --> 00:12:03.639
That he kent Roger and Brianna...

199
00:12:05.724 --> 00:12:06.851
from Scotland.

200
00:12:08.269 --> 00:12:09.770
He says he's looking for them...

201
00:12:10.771 --> 00:12:11.981
- Cameron.
- Aye.

202
00:12:18.362 --> 00:12:20.156
[suspenseful music playing]

203
00:12:28.038 --> 00:12:28.956
[pistol cocks]

204
00:12:29.039 --> 00:12:32.001
I'm James Fraser. I understand
you're acquainted

205
00:12:32.084 --> 00:12:34.211
with my daughter. Brianna MacKenzie.

206
00:12:34.295 --> 00:12:35.963
[man] I am. Aye.

207
00:12:37.548 --> 00:12:39.592
You're Robert Cameron then.

208
00:12:39.675 --> 00:12:41.051
Christ. no. man.

209
00:12:42.094 --> 00:12:43.345
I'm no Rob Cameron.

210
00:12:46.056 --> 00:12:48.601
{\an8}My name is William Buccleigh MacKenzie.

211
00:12:50.019 --> 00:12:54.815
Come to tell Roger and Brianna that
Cameron won't be bothering them again.

212
00:12:55.691 --> 00:12:58.027
And to return... Roger's wee book.

213
00:13:02.323 --> 00:13:05.534
Don't want it fallin' in the wrong hands
a second time.

214
00:13:12.833 --> 00:13:13.918
Buck MacKenzie.

215
00:13:16.879 --> 00:13:18.589
You remind me of your father.

216
00:13:22.426 --> 00:13:23.260
[horse whinnies]

217
00:13:23.344 --> 00:13:25.387
Perhaps when you've finished
painting Lady Grey.

218
00:13:25.471 --> 00:13:28.098
you could paint a portrait
of Marsali and me.

219
00:13:28.182 --> 00:13:30.893
I'd be happy to.
I'll paint the whole family.

220
00:13:30.976 --> 00:13:34.480
We need to send to Philadelphia
for a canvas big enough.

221
00:13:34.980 --> 00:13:37.650
- [chuckles]
- Don't linger at the Continental Camp.

222
00:13:38.442 --> 00:13:41.237
Talk among the merchants
is that the battle is imminent.

223
00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:42.905
I'll return as soon as I'm able.

224
00:13:44.114 --> 00:13:46.325
- Be safe.
- You too. See you soon.

225
00:13:47.535 --> 00:13:49.787
With any luck. I'll see you both soon.

226
00:13:49.870 --> 00:13:50.871
Good luck.

227
00:13:54.416 --> 00:13:55.584
[rustling]

228
00:13:56.919 --> 00:13:58.295
[wind whistling]

229
00:14:02.716 --> 00:14:04.009
[wood creaking]

230
00:14:10.266 --> 00:14:12.351
Do you think houses are alive?

231
00:14:13.185 --> 00:14:14.520
That was the wind.

232
00:14:15.312 --> 00:14:16.981
[wood continues creaking]

233
00:14:17.690 --> 00:14:18.899
But yes.

234
00:14:19.733 --> 00:14:24.238
I think places
that people live in for a time

235
00:14:25.155 --> 00:14:27.616
absorb a little bit of them.

236
00:14:29.034 --> 00:14:33.372
I often think that houses
affect the people living in them.

237
00:14:34.164 --> 00:14:36.417
so why wouldn't it work both ways?

238
00:14:39.461 --> 00:14:44.258
So. do you think Amy Lindsay's
still in her cabin. haunting it?

239
00:14:45.384 --> 00:14:47.595
I don't know about her cabin exactly.

240
00:14:51.140 --> 00:14:52.349
When people die...

241
00:14:53.684 --> 00:14:57.730
naturally. the people
they leave behind sense them.

242
00:14:58.230 --> 00:14:59.440
You know. sense...

243
00:15:00.816 --> 00:15:03.110
that a part of them
are still with them in a way.

244
00:15:03.193 --> 00:15:05.988
I don't know that I would call
that haunting. though.

245
00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:11.869
It's more like... a memory. a longing.

246
00:15:15.122 --> 00:15:16.790
[softly] I wish Jane would haunt me.

247
00:15:18.334 --> 00:15:19.543
Fanny...

248
00:15:25.215 --> 00:15:29.929
You won't forget her.
And she won't forget you either.

249
00:15:32.973 --> 00:15:36.352
You know. talking about
the people we've lost

250
00:15:37.603 --> 00:15:40.648
can make it seem as though
they're still with us.

251
00:15:42.733 --> 00:15:44.360
[crying softly]

252
00:15:44.652 --> 00:15:49.114
Janie used to whisper
"Good night. <i>ma chérie."</i>

253
00:15:49.907 --> 00:15:51.325
before we went to sleep.

254
00:15:54.954 --> 00:15:57.873
- She spoke French?
- A little.

255
00:15:58.999 --> 00:16:03.003
She said that's what our mother
used to call me. <i>ma chérie.</i>

256
00:16:04.296 --> 00:16:07.257
Janie used to tell me
about our parents before bed.

257
00:16:12.221 --> 00:16:15.057
She was trying to help you
keep the memory alive.

258
00:16:16.350 --> 00:16:20.396
She would tell me good things.
Or funny things.

259
00:16:21.563 --> 00:16:25.234
But we would never talk about...
anything serious.

260
00:16:25.901 --> 00:16:28.028
She talked to the other girls
at the brothel.

261
00:16:28.112 --> 00:16:30.280
I know she was trying to protect me.

262
00:16:30.781 --> 00:16:32.574
Sometimes I wish she hadn't.

263
00:16:35.244 --> 00:16:37.121
- [wind whistling]
- [clattering]

264
00:16:40.833 --> 00:16:42.876
I better go close that window.

265
00:16:47.089 --> 00:16:48.382
[creaking. clattering]

266
00:16:52.344 --> 00:16:53.554
[intriguing music playing]

267
00:17:00.436 --> 00:17:02.229
And your little dog. too.

268
00:17:02.312 --> 00:17:03.689
[Frances] What did you say?

269
00:17:06.191 --> 00:17:08.527
Mrs. Cunningham's coming.

270
00:17:08.610 --> 00:17:10.779
Could you show her in?
I'll be right there.

271
00:17:10.863 --> 00:17:12.573
She's come
for the slippery elm powder

272
00:17:12.656 --> 00:17:13.657
I promised her.

273
00:17:15.909 --> 00:17:17.995
[Frances] Good evening. Mrs. Cunningham.

274
00:17:18.078 --> 00:17:19.747
Do you want to wait in the parlor?

275
00:17:19.830 --> 00:17:21.874
[Elspeth] I most certainly will not wait!

276
00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:24.084
I need help!

277
00:17:25.044 --> 00:17:26.170
[groaning]

278
00:17:27.337 --> 00:17:28.297
Frances. chair.

279
00:17:31.967 --> 00:17:33.635
Go get some whiskey. please.

280
00:17:35.304 --> 00:17:37.514
- What happened?
- Fell.

281
00:17:38.432 --> 00:17:42.144
Tripped over the scuttle like a fool
and fell on my shoulder.

282
00:17:42.227 --> 00:17:43.520
Don't worry.

283
00:17:43.604 --> 00:17:44.605
I can fix it.

284
00:17:44.688 --> 00:17:47.858
I wouldn't have staggered two miles
through buggering brambles

285
00:17:47.941 --> 00:17:49.610
if I didn't think you could.

286
00:17:51.403 --> 00:17:53.155
And where is your son?

287
00:17:53.322 --> 00:17:54.156
[Elspeth] Mmm.

288
00:17:54.615 --> 00:17:55.741
He's away.

289
00:18:04.541 --> 00:18:05.375
[gasps sharply]

290
00:18:09.004 --> 00:18:11.381
[Claire] As I thought. dislocated.

291
00:18:17.346 --> 00:18:18.263
Fanny.

292
00:18:19.723 --> 00:18:22.101
Hold her tight... here.

293
00:18:23.102 --> 00:18:24.978
That's it. Elspeth.

294
00:18:26.313 --> 00:18:27.689
this is going to hurt.

295
00:18:28.565 --> 00:18:29.566
[Elspeth whimpering]

296
00:18:38.325 --> 00:18:39.368
[exhales shakily]

297
00:18:39.451 --> 00:18:40.410
[Claire] All right.

298
00:18:42.079 --> 00:18:42.913
Ready?

299
00:18:44.623 --> 00:18:45.541
[Elspeth whimpers]

300
00:18:47.793 --> 00:18:49.211
- [bone pops]
- [Elspeth gasps]

301
00:18:49.878 --> 00:18:53.257
{\an8}Grass-combing son of a buggering sod!

302
00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:02.766
What. child?

303
00:19:02.850 --> 00:19:06.186
It's been a long time
since I heard language like that.

304
00:19:07.187 --> 00:19:09.731
Well. if you have to do
with soldiers. young woman.

305
00:19:09.815 --> 00:19:13.277
you acquire their vices
as well as their virtues.

306
00:19:14.736 --> 00:19:17.531
Where. may I ask. did you hear
language like that?

307
00:19:17.614 --> 00:19:19.074
I lived in a brothel.

308
00:19:20.033 --> 00:19:20.993
Indeed.

309
00:19:23.162 --> 00:19:28.667
Well. I suppose whores also have
their virtues as well as their vices.

310
00:19:29.168 --> 00:19:30.794
[Frances] I don't know.

311
00:19:30.878 --> 00:19:34.590
Unless you count being able to satisfy
a man in two minutes by the clock.

312
00:19:34.673 --> 00:19:35.507
[coughs]

313
00:19:35.591 --> 00:19:40.220
Oh. my. I think that would be classed
as a skill rather than a virtue.

314
00:19:41.430 --> 00:19:43.765
Though a useful one. I daresay.

315
00:19:43.849 --> 00:19:46.685
I'm sure everyone has their strong points.

316
00:19:46.768 --> 00:19:51.148
Fanny. would you go to the kitchen
and make up a plate for Mrs. Cunningham?

317
00:19:53.901 --> 00:19:58.655
You know. I have always wondered
about the term "grass-combing."

318
00:19:59.698 --> 00:20:03.535
Is it actual bad language
or is it just descriptive?

319
00:20:04.203 --> 00:20:09.374
Well. it usually applies to someone
who is either idle or incompetent.

320
00:20:10.250 --> 00:20:15.297
Why combing grass should invoke
either attribute is unclear.

321
00:20:15.964 --> 00:20:20.677
but it isn't actually bad language
unless the term "bugger" is applied.

322
00:20:21.178 --> 00:20:24.056
I've never actually
heard it without "bugger."

323
00:20:26.642 --> 00:20:30.479
You must have heard much more
if you were traveling with the army.

324
00:20:31.021 --> 00:20:32.689
Oh. it's worse than you think.

325
00:20:33.649 --> 00:20:35.901
My first husband was a sailor.

326
00:20:37.903 --> 00:20:40.530
Well. I believe you've shocked Fanny.

327
00:20:41.698 --> 00:20:47.329
not with the actual language. but that it
came from a respectable woman such as you.

328
00:20:48.163 --> 00:20:52.918
Well. women tend to be freer in their
speech when there aren't any men present.

329
00:20:54.628 --> 00:20:56.505
She's a remarkable child.

330
00:20:57.130 --> 00:20:58.882
You must try to persuade her not to...

331
00:20:58.966 --> 00:21:02.636
She knows not to talk like that in public.
as I'm sure do you.

332
00:21:02.803 --> 00:21:03.637
[chuckles softly]

333
00:21:03.929 --> 00:21:06.473
But you're free to say anything
you like here tonight.

334
00:21:06.556 --> 00:21:09.768
as I'm not letting you go back
to your cabin in your condition.

335
00:21:09.851 --> 00:21:14.982
By my condition whether you mean
injured or inebriated. I'm not sure.

336
00:21:15.065 --> 00:21:17.150
but in either case. thank you.

337
00:21:36.086 --> 00:21:37.129
William.

338
00:21:37.713 --> 00:21:39.423
Bloody hell. it's you.

339
00:21:39.756 --> 00:21:40.841
[door opens]

340
00:21:42.968 --> 00:21:45.679
William. would you like
to invite our guest in?

341
00:21:45.762 --> 00:21:47.806
She's had quite a long journey.

342
00:21:47.889 --> 00:21:49.516
Forgive me. Mrs. MacKenzie.

343
00:21:50.183 --> 00:21:53.854
The unexpected pleasure of seeing you
again has caused me to forget myself.

344
00:22:02.738 --> 00:22:05.574
I was delighted when you accepted
my invitation. my dear.

345
00:22:05.657 --> 00:22:08.493
I was beginning to fear
I'd never see you again.

346
00:22:08.577 --> 00:22:10.912
Feels like a lifetime since we all met.

347
00:22:11.621 --> 00:22:16.168
Allow me to introduce Amaranthus.
Viscountess Grey. My late nephew's widow.

348
00:22:17.461 --> 00:22:18.462
A pleasure.

349
00:22:18.962 --> 00:22:21.089
I'm sorry for your loss.

350
00:22:22.299 --> 00:22:25.302
Lord John mentioned
he'd sent for a portrait painter.

351
00:22:25.802 --> 00:22:27.971
Didn't realize it would be a woman.

352
00:22:28.055 --> 00:22:30.515
You must be very skilled
for him to ask you to come.

353
00:22:31.183 --> 00:22:33.977
- Where is it you traveled from?
- North Carolina.

354
00:22:34.561 --> 00:22:36.688
Well. surely you did not
undertake the journey alone.

355
00:22:36.772 --> 00:22:40.400
I was under the impression that
your husband would be accompanying you.

356
00:22:40.484 --> 00:22:45.155
He did. but he's currently attending
to an errand outside the city.

357
00:22:45.739 --> 00:22:47.866
It's time for Trevor's bedtime feed.

358
00:22:48.408 --> 00:22:50.702
It was a pleasure. Mrs. MacKenzie.

359
00:22:55.123 --> 00:23:00.921
Yes. well. uh. various important matters
require my attention.

360
00:23:01.004 --> 00:23:05.592
So I will leave you two
to become reacquainted.

361
00:23:11.348 --> 00:23:13.350
[both chuckle softly]

362
00:23:14.476 --> 00:23:16.603
You came from North Carolina?

363
00:23:16.686 --> 00:23:19.314
Last we met.
you were on your way to Boston.

364
00:23:19.397 --> 00:23:20.941
These are dangerous times.

365
00:23:21.483 --> 00:23:25.070
We thought it best to be with family.
so we returned to Fraser's Ridge.

366
00:23:25.862 --> 00:23:27.656
You must have met Fanny. then.

367
00:23:28.156 --> 00:23:30.742
- Is she well?
- [laughs happily] Yes. she is.

368
00:23:30.826 --> 00:23:33.537
My mother has taken quite a liking to her.

369
00:23:34.871 --> 00:23:35.872
So has my father.

370
00:23:37.374 --> 00:23:41.002
Well. I mean. our father.

371
00:23:44.214 --> 00:23:45.048
[scoffs lightly]

372
00:23:47.384 --> 00:23:49.052
Did you know?

373
00:23:49.136 --> 00:23:53.223
The day we met in Wilmington.
did you know what we were to each other?

374
00:23:55.600 --> 00:23:56.476
I did.

375
00:23:57.853 --> 00:23:59.104
I wanted to tell you.

376
00:24:00.063 --> 00:24:01.940
Roger. my husband. was with me.

377
00:24:02.023 --> 00:24:04.860
He was just around the corner at the inn.

378
00:24:05.360 --> 00:24:07.320
And my children. Jem and Mandy.

379
00:24:07.988 --> 00:24:08.822
I...

380
00:24:09.698 --> 00:24:11.783
really wanted you to meet them.

381
00:24:13.201 --> 00:24:15.829
Even if you didn't know we were...

382
00:24:17.622 --> 00:24:19.958
well. yours.

383
00:24:20.917 --> 00:24:22.043
Mine?

384
00:24:24.212 --> 00:24:26.089
I should probably say something polite

385
00:24:26.173 --> 00:24:28.550
like. "Only if you want us." but that's...

386
00:24:28.633 --> 00:24:29.843
A bit late for that.

387
00:24:29.926 --> 00:24:31.970
To lie about the truth. I mean.

388
00:24:33.763 --> 00:24:36.641
I do apologize for not telling you.

389
00:24:37.559 --> 00:24:40.770
But Lord John and Da
felt so strongly that...

390
00:24:43.940 --> 00:24:45.233
It wasn't my place.

391
00:24:47.319 --> 00:24:48.904
I accept your apology.

392
00:24:50.197 --> 00:24:53.200
Though. in all honesty.
I'm glad you didn't tell me.

393
00:24:54.784 --> 00:24:58.663
I wouldn't have known how to respond
to such a revelation at the time.

394
00:24:58.872 --> 00:24:59.706
Hmm.

395
00:25:00.498 --> 00:25:01.917
And you do now?

396
00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:03.877
- No. I bloody don't.
- [laughs]

397
00:25:06.046 --> 00:25:08.048
But I haven't blown my brains out.

398
00:25:08.506 --> 00:25:10.175
When I was 18. I might have.

399
00:25:13.053 --> 00:25:14.054
I apologize.

400
00:25:14.596 --> 00:25:18.225
I didn't mean that with any derogatory
reference to you or your family.

401
00:25:19.184 --> 00:25:21.394
Your family. you mean.

402
00:25:33.949 --> 00:25:35.450
[Percival] Thank you for coming.

403
00:25:35.533 --> 00:25:37.244
Allow me to send for wine.

404
00:25:37.327 --> 00:25:39.704
No. thank you.
Came to hear what you have to say.

405
00:25:39.788 --> 00:25:41.665
but I must get back to my work.

406
00:25:42.791 --> 00:25:44.000
Very well then. sir.

407
00:25:44.960 --> 00:25:46.211
I'll get right to it.

408
00:25:49.839 --> 00:25:52.884
I wish to acquaint you
with the facts of your birth.

409
00:25:54.427 --> 00:25:56.221
Facts I think you do not know.

410
00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:01.935
Have you heard of a man
by the name of le Comte St. Germain?

411
00:26:04.396 --> 00:26:05.689
Why?

412
00:26:06.189 --> 00:26:07.482
You are his son.

413
00:26:12.153 --> 00:26:16.283
I'm sure you'll have an explanation
as to how you came to this

414
00:26:16.366 --> 00:26:17.909
preposterous conclusion.

415
00:26:19.494 --> 00:26:22.330
As you may have surmised.
I am not French myself.

416
00:26:23.290 --> 00:26:26.751
I have. however. married
into a prestigious French family.

417
00:26:27.544 --> 00:26:30.588
My wife is the sister
of the Baron Amandine.

418
00:26:30.672 --> 00:26:36.761
and as with any old dynasty.
there is a sordid family secret.

419
00:26:38.221 --> 00:26:41.933
Many years ago. my wife's older sister
began a torrid affair with the Comte.

420
00:26:42.017 --> 00:26:46.438
and not long after disappeared.
fled into the night with her jewels

421
00:26:46.521 --> 00:26:49.607
and they supposed into
the arms of another lover.

422
00:26:51.067 --> 00:26:54.696
I take it you wish me to believe
I'm the result of this tryst.

423
00:26:55.905 --> 00:26:59.409
Perhaps the name of the woman
in question will convince you.

424
00:27:00.618 --> 00:27:02.329
Amélie LeVigne Beauchamp.

425
00:27:06.166 --> 00:27:07.334
[speaking French]

426
00:27:11.254 --> 00:27:12.172
[in English] Yes.

427
00:27:12.922 --> 00:27:14.090
Yes. She is dead.

428
00:27:15.675 --> 00:27:16.801
You may continue.

429
00:27:18.094 --> 00:27:22.307
A few years ago. I uncovered the truth
from one of the Comte's servants.

430
00:27:23.058 --> 00:27:25.352
Amélie did not run away with a lover.

431
00:27:25.435 --> 00:27:27.312
The Comte simply grew weary of her

432
00:27:27.395 --> 00:27:30.648
and learning she was pregnant.
lured her away from home.

433
00:27:30.732 --> 00:27:33.735
drugged her with opium
and sold her to a brothel.

434
00:27:36.696 --> 00:27:37.697
Maison Elise.

435
00:27:37.781 --> 00:27:40.241
That is where she gave birth to a child.

436
00:27:41.743 --> 00:27:42.577
You.

437
00:27:46.623 --> 00:27:47.707
<i>Et Monsieur</i> le Comte?

438
00:27:48.208 --> 00:27:52.462
He was last seen more than 30 years ago.
And while no body was found.

439
00:27:52.545 --> 00:27:55.465
the circumstances of his disappearance
were so mysterious

440
00:27:55.548 --> 00:27:57.550
that a magistrate declared him deceased.

441
00:27:58.510 --> 00:28:03.181
His estate is currently held in trust
by a solicitor in Paris.

442
00:28:04.140 --> 00:28:10.647
But it would undoubtedly be released
should a petition be filed by his heir.

443
00:28:13.233 --> 00:28:15.652
Unless the law in France has
changed of late.

444
00:28:16.236 --> 00:28:18.613
a bastard cannot inherit properties. so...

445
00:28:19.739 --> 00:28:24.911
Claudel. If I may use your original name.

446
00:28:31.793 --> 00:28:33.378
You may not. sir.

447
00:28:34.587 --> 00:28:35.505
Very well.

448
00:28:37.340 --> 00:28:41.636
I found this. hidden in the pages
of a dusty family Bible.

449
00:28:42.429 --> 00:28:46.474
I'm quite certain I'm the only one living
who knows of its existence.

450
00:28:49.144 --> 00:28:50.854
It is a contract of marriage.

451
00:29:10.457 --> 00:29:14.544
It appears Amélie relinquished
her virtue at a high price

452
00:29:14.627 --> 00:29:20.633
by demanding the Comte marry her in secret
before welcoming him to her bed.

453
00:29:25.847 --> 00:29:27.849
Allow me to congratulate you. sir.

454
00:29:29.225 --> 00:29:30.643
You are not a bastard.

455
00:29:32.395 --> 00:29:34.481
Assuming the document isn't forged.

456
00:29:35.482 --> 00:29:38.318
plainly. you have something
you want out of this.

457
00:29:39.402 --> 00:29:42.906
Something <i>Monsieur</i> le Comte's heir
might accomplish for you?

458
00:29:42.989 --> 00:29:44.866
Le Comte St. Germain owned his estate.

459
00:29:44.949 --> 00:29:47.702
still does own a majority
of the stock of a syndicate

460
00:29:47.786 --> 00:29:49.871
investing in land in the New World.

461
00:29:49.954 --> 00:29:54.709
The main asset of which is a large parcel
in what is known as the Old Northwest.

462
00:29:55.877 --> 00:30:00.548
Some interests of mine in Paris
believe that while Britain

463
00:30:00.632 --> 00:30:04.677
is preoccupied with this rebellion.
there is an opportunity

464
00:30:04.761 --> 00:30:09.891
to establish a French colony
on the land with French settlers.

465
00:30:11.810 --> 00:30:17.106
Unfortunately. le Comte's solicitor
refuses to sell the stock at any price.

466
00:30:21.528 --> 00:30:26.324
But if a legitimate heir were to appear.
the land would become his.

467
00:30:26.407 --> 00:30:31.246
And my associates would pay said heir
a significant sum for said land.

468
00:30:33.873 --> 00:30:36.668
A significant sum.

469
00:30:45.802 --> 00:30:47.637
Have I done something to offend you?

470
00:30:48.346 --> 00:30:50.890
I'm simply trying to enjoy
my literature in solitude.

471
00:30:50.974 --> 00:30:55.019
Should you require company.
perhaps Mrs. MacKenzie will oblige you.

472
00:30:56.271 --> 00:30:58.106
Lady Grey. are you jealous?

473
00:30:58.606 --> 00:30:59.983
Don't be absurd.

474
00:31:01.776 --> 00:31:05.238
Though anyone with eyes can see that
there's a history between the two of you.

475
00:31:05.405 --> 00:31:06.239
[scoffs]

476
00:31:07.365 --> 00:31:08.741
I suppose you're right.

477
00:31:08.825 --> 00:31:11.411
She's a person of some
significance in my life. but...

478
00:31:11.494 --> 00:31:12.579
Please.

479
00:31:13.162 --> 00:31:14.455
I thought we...

480
00:31:15.248 --> 00:31:16.291
[chuckles nervously]

481
00:31:16.416 --> 00:31:17.750
It doesn't matter.

482
00:31:17.834 --> 00:31:18.835
It was foolish.

483
00:31:21.963 --> 00:31:23.089
Miss MacKenzie...

484
00:31:23.172 --> 00:31:25.466
Brianna is my sister.

485
00:31:30.555 --> 00:31:32.390
You told me you didn't have any siblings.

486
00:31:35.476 --> 00:31:36.311
[sighs]

487
00:31:37.562 --> 00:31:38.646
I'm a bastard.

488
00:31:39.647 --> 00:31:42.775
Well. I'm not legally a bastard
since the Eighth Earl of Ellesmere

489
00:31:42.859 --> 00:31:45.028
and my mother were married
when I was born.

490
00:31:45.904 --> 00:31:48.948
But the Eighth Earl was not my father.

491
00:31:50.867 --> 00:31:53.703
The man who sired me was...

492
00:31:53.786 --> 00:31:56.748
is. Brianna's father.

493
00:31:59.751 --> 00:32:04.088
Well. whoever he was.
he must have been a...

494
00:32:05.465 --> 00:32:07.592
a very striking gentleman.

495
00:32:09.761 --> 00:32:10.887
He is.

496
00:32:12.931 --> 00:32:14.432
Has he acknowledged you?

497
00:32:14.515 --> 00:32:15.558
Not publicly. no.

498
00:32:16.476 --> 00:32:17.769
Nor do I want him to.

499
00:32:18.686 --> 00:32:19.812
He owes me nothing.

500
00:32:22.148 --> 00:32:25.526
I'm only telling you this
because you asked.

501
00:32:28.071 --> 00:32:29.656
Because I enjoy your company.

502
00:32:31.699 --> 00:32:34.369
May I be so bold
as to presume you enjoy mine?

503
00:32:39.749 --> 00:32:40.875
That is bold.

504
00:32:44.671 --> 00:32:46.422
Though perhaps not incorrect.

505
00:32:48.716 --> 00:32:49.550
Well...

506
00:32:50.677 --> 00:32:53.638
I think it only fair one comprehends

507
00:32:53.721 --> 00:32:55.223
a person whose company one enjoys.

508
00:32:58.851 --> 00:33:01.187
I am not the Ninth Earl of Ellesmere.

509
00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:03.398
Not really.

510
00:33:04.649 --> 00:33:06.067
I never was.

511
00:33:07.318 --> 00:33:11.948
Of late. I've found myself wishing I could
renounce the damn title altogether.

512
00:33:12.031 --> 00:33:15.284
though English law
makes that all but impossible.

513
00:33:15.368 --> 00:33:17.495
Well. you may not be able to renounce it.

514
00:33:17.578 --> 00:33:22.041
but you could hand it on.
abdicate in favor of your heir. I mean.

515
00:33:22.125 --> 00:33:23.668
I don't have an heir.

516
00:33:24.502 --> 00:33:27.463
Well. you could marry me
and give it to our firstborn.

517
00:33:28.798 --> 00:33:30.800
I'm a widow after all.

518
00:33:32.093 --> 00:33:35.888
We could retire into private life
and breed Dachshunds.

519
00:33:40.184 --> 00:33:42.061
I can't imagine anything more tiresome.

520
00:33:42.895 --> 00:33:47.734
Surely you don't mean to imply that being
married to me would be tiresome. William.

521
00:33:48.234 --> 00:33:49.944
You might just possibly enjoy it.

522
00:33:53.948 --> 00:33:56.075
Thank you. Amaranthus...

523
00:33:57.160 --> 00:33:59.620
for not thinking less of me.

524
00:34:02.165 --> 00:34:06.753
As I've told you. I'm the daughter
of F. Cowden. bookseller.

525
00:34:08.921 --> 00:34:11.132
That's all my father is to the world.

526
00:34:12.425 --> 00:34:14.761
I thought I would be a merchant's wife.

527
00:34:17.013 --> 00:34:19.390
But now I am Viscountess Grey.

528
00:34:22.018 --> 00:34:24.395
And my son will be the Duke of Pardloe.

529
00:34:26.355 --> 00:34:30.651
While you may disagree. I believe
a title is something you simply have.

530
00:34:31.277 --> 00:34:32.612
Not something you are.

531
00:34:33.780 --> 00:34:36.199
By law. you are the Earl of Ellesmere.

532
00:34:36.783 --> 00:34:38.451
That's all the world needs to know.

533
00:34:39.994 --> 00:34:41.954
[gentle music playing]

534
00:34:45.374 --> 00:34:48.878
But you're not only that. William.
Not to me.

535
00:34:53.841 --> 00:34:55.259
How's the pain?

536
00:34:55.343 --> 00:34:57.261
In my shoulder or my head?

537
00:34:58.721 --> 00:35:00.306
Both. I suppose.

538
00:35:00.389 --> 00:35:01.390
Bearable.

539
00:35:01.474 --> 00:35:02.517
[clattering]

540
00:35:02.975 --> 00:35:06.229
Though I wish the girl
would refrain from slamming doors.

541
00:35:06.312 --> 00:35:07.814
That's not Fanny.

542
00:35:08.689 --> 00:35:11.400
She's taking milk over to Evan Lindsay's.

543
00:35:12.235 --> 00:35:15.279
- Then who?
- Houses make sounds. Elspeth.

544
00:35:15.363 --> 00:35:18.574
And all I know is that when
the wind is in the east.

545
00:35:18.658 --> 00:35:21.661
ours makes that particular
noise from the attic.

546
00:35:21.744 --> 00:35:24.080
Why build an attic in the first place?

547
00:35:25.456 --> 00:35:28.835
Because my husband
is the Fraser of Fraser's Ridge.

548
00:35:29.752 --> 00:35:32.380
If there should ever be
any kind of emergency

549
00:35:32.463 --> 00:35:34.465
that causes our tenants
to leave their home.

550
00:35:34.549 --> 00:35:38.302
well. then they can take
refuge here with us.

551
00:35:38.928 --> 00:35:41.722
And what kind of an emergency
might that be?

552
00:35:49.438 --> 00:35:50.439
Your son.

553
00:35:51.357 --> 00:35:56.028
- Do you believe what he says about...
- My grandson's death?

554
00:35:56.988 --> 00:35:59.073
Yes. I do believe him.

555
00:35:59.907 --> 00:36:01.200
It is a comfort.

556
00:36:03.119 --> 00:36:07.498
I was thinking specifically about
what he said to him.

557
00:36:08.624 --> 00:36:12.920
That he. your grandson. would see Charles
again in seven years' time.

558
00:36:14.005 --> 00:36:15.214
Do you believe that?

559
00:36:16.549 --> 00:36:18.509
I only know that he believes it.

560
00:36:20.344 --> 00:36:21.345
[knocking at door]

561
00:36:26.976 --> 00:36:28.352
Good day. Mrs. Fraser.

562
00:36:29.145 --> 00:36:30.605
I'm here to collect my mother.

563
00:36:31.272 --> 00:36:33.107
I'll help her get her things.

564
00:36:33.191 --> 00:36:35.443
No need. I'll do it myself.

565
00:36:40.823 --> 00:36:42.825
You'll find her through here.

566
00:36:46.078 --> 00:36:48.706
Mother. are you well?
I heard that you were injured.

567
00:36:48.789 --> 00:36:50.208
Yes. my shoulder.

568
00:36:50.291 --> 00:36:53.711
But Mrs. Fraser was able
to heal it quite satisfactorily.

569
00:36:54.337 --> 00:36:56.631
She's been most hospitable.

570
00:36:56.714 --> 00:36:58.466
I've enjoyed the company.

571
00:36:58.549 --> 00:37:01.302
Her husband's away
at the moment on business.

572
00:37:01.385 --> 00:37:03.721
Is he? I had wondered.

573
00:37:04.680 --> 00:37:06.682
He's a hard man to pin down. your husband.

574
00:37:06.766 --> 00:37:08.851
We had been meaning to talk.

575
00:37:09.936 --> 00:37:11.729
Or so I thought.

576
00:37:11.979 --> 00:37:13.064
[chuckles nervously]

577
00:37:13.231 --> 00:37:15.441
Well. he's anxious to speak with you. too.

578
00:37:15.983 --> 00:37:18.986
But this business couldn't wait.

579
00:37:19.779 --> 00:37:24.283
Well. I thank you. ma'am.
for the care you've shown my mother.

580
00:37:26.077 --> 00:37:28.746
She should be fully recovered
within a week or so.

581
00:37:28.829 --> 00:37:33.584
But here are some herbs
that should ease her discomfort.

582
00:37:36.671 --> 00:37:38.965
You have a very fine home.

583
00:37:39.590 --> 00:37:42.510
It must feel very empty with him away

584
00:37:42.593 --> 00:37:44.136
and you here all alone.

585
00:37:52.687 --> 00:37:55.773
I'm fine. I can assure you.

586
00:37:58.276 --> 00:38:00.278
I expect him home at any moment.

587
00:38:01.028 --> 00:38:03.030
I'll let him know you stopped by.

588
00:38:04.115 --> 00:38:05.741
[tense music playing]

589
00:38:06.659 --> 00:38:10.371
- Charles. did you bring the cart?
- Of course. Mother.

590
00:38:16.752 --> 00:38:19.255
Until next time. Mrs. Fraser.

591
00:38:23.926 --> 00:38:26.470
[door opens. closes]

592
00:38:29.557 --> 00:38:31.559
Do you think he's telling you the truth?

593
00:38:31.642 --> 00:38:33.060
He very well may be.

594
00:38:34.729 --> 00:38:36.814
Amélie. I knew her. but I...

595
00:38:38.232 --> 00:38:39.150
[exhales]

596
00:38:39.525 --> 00:38:41.610
I didn't know she was my mother.

597
00:38:43.529 --> 00:38:45.698
There are many children born in a brothel.

598
00:38:46.282 --> 00:38:48.701
The little ones. they would call
any whore <i>maman.</i>

599
00:38:48.784 --> 00:38:50.619
Anyone who would feed them.

600
00:38:51.287 --> 00:38:53.164
And if a whore had to attend a customer

601
00:38:53.247 --> 00:38:56.834
and a child was hungry. she'd just
hand him to another <i>jeune fille.</i>

602
00:38:58.502 --> 00:39:02.006
Amélie. they call her "The Baroness"
for her haughty manner.

603
00:39:05.551 --> 00:39:07.803
Even then. I knew the name was cruel.

604
00:39:07.887 --> 00:39:10.514
but until today.
I didn't realize how cruel.

605
00:39:19.357 --> 00:39:20.983
Was she kind to you?

606
00:39:21.567 --> 00:39:24.779
She detested all of the children
of the brothel. but...

607
00:39:26.364 --> 00:39:27.406
me most of all.

608
00:39:30.451 --> 00:39:31.952
I understand now.

609
00:39:32.036 --> 00:39:35.331
I was the spawn of the man who took
everything from her.

610
00:39:36.457 --> 00:39:37.541
Her love.

611
00:39:38.959 --> 00:39:40.086
Her freedom.

612
00:39:41.837 --> 00:39:42.963
Even her family.

613
00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:50.012
I think I was maybe six years old
when she died.

614
00:39:50.096 --> 00:39:52.348
She contracted the morbid sore throat.

615
00:39:56.352 --> 00:39:58.771
I remember she summoned me to her chamber.

616
00:40:00.815 --> 00:40:01.857
What did she say?

617
00:40:03.192 --> 00:40:04.026
[speaking French]

618
00:40:06.487 --> 00:40:07.571
[in English] Be a good boy.

619
00:40:08.197 --> 00:40:09.740
[scoffs]

620
00:40:18.958 --> 00:40:21.961
It wasna fair for her to blame you
for what happened to her.

621
00:40:23.254 --> 00:40:25.131
I wouldn't expect fairness from one

622
00:40:25.214 --> 00:40:27.758
whose life was filled
with so much cruelty.

623
00:40:28.509 --> 00:40:30.344
At the hands of such a villain.

624
00:40:32.430 --> 00:40:35.724
Le Comte St. Germain. in France.
he tried to kill milady.

625
00:40:37.101 --> 00:40:39.186
And now to learn that he sired me...

626
00:40:40.187 --> 00:40:41.147
You are not him.

627
00:40:42.565 --> 00:40:44.483
I know that better than anyone. my love.

628
00:40:45.526 --> 00:40:50.364
But if you are truly his heir. then
you can use what he has left you for good.

629
00:40:51.157 --> 00:40:53.451
If you take this Beauchamp
up on his offer...

630
00:40:53.534 --> 00:40:55.161
That man is a whore.

631
00:40:55.244 --> 00:40:56.162
I should know.

632
00:40:57.371 --> 00:40:59.081
He's likely been one all his life.

633
00:40:59.165 --> 00:41:01.208
<i>Monsieur</i> Beauchamp is too old
to sell his arse.

634
00:41:01.292 --> 00:41:04.295
but he would sell himself from necessity.

635
00:41:04.378 --> 00:41:08.215
All he's asking. though.
is that you sell him some land. no?

636
00:41:09.175 --> 00:41:11.552
Land that you have a right to by birth.

637
00:41:11.635 --> 00:41:12.720
Yes. but why?

638
00:41:13.971 --> 00:41:17.808
What effect will that have selling it
to these interests in Paris?

639
00:41:17.892 --> 00:41:21.395
He wants to install a French colony
on American soil. but...

640
00:41:22.271 --> 00:41:25.107
we've devoted ourselves
to the Patriot cause.

641
00:41:27.193 --> 00:41:29.403
We're not fighting
to be free of a British king

642
00:41:29.487 --> 00:41:31.864
just to become servants of a French one.

643
00:41:32.573 --> 00:41:34.366
You dinna ken it'll come to that.

644
00:41:36.410 --> 00:41:38.120
You don't know that it won't.

645
00:41:39.914 --> 00:41:41.540
That isn't everythin'.

646
00:41:42.124 --> 00:41:43.709
I ken you. Fergus Fraser.

647
00:41:45.044 --> 00:41:47.963
Why is this offer so difficult
to consider?

648
00:41:49.215 --> 00:41:52.343
To claim this inheritance. this land.

649
00:41:54.470 --> 00:41:58.432
I must publicly acknowledge
that le Comte St. Germain was my father.

650
00:42:00.851 --> 00:42:03.896
<i>Monsieur</i> Beauchamp told me
what every orphan wants to hear.

651
00:42:04.813 --> 00:42:06.732
That I'm the son of a great man.

652
00:42:11.111 --> 00:42:14.532
But I'm already the son of a great man.

653
00:42:28.796 --> 00:42:29.797
[distant explosions]

654
00:42:31.382 --> 00:42:32.716
Do not worry. my dear.

655
00:42:33.467 --> 00:42:37.471
A French warship. the <i>Truite.</i> has taken
to firing her cannon on occasion.

656
00:42:38.347 --> 00:42:39.598
A dreadful nuisance.

657
00:42:41.141 --> 00:42:44.144
She's anchored on the far end
of Hutchinson Island.

658
00:42:44.228 --> 00:42:46.814
out of range to do any damage
here in town.

659
00:42:49.024 --> 00:42:52.027
I assure you. you're perfectly safe.

660
00:42:52.736 --> 00:42:53.946
[distant explosions continue]

661
00:42:54.613 --> 00:42:56.407
Oh. glad to hear it.

662
00:42:58.659 --> 00:43:02.246
So why didn't you
tell William I was coming?

663
00:43:04.206 --> 00:43:05.624
Because. um...

664
00:43:07.209 --> 00:43:09.253
Because I didn't know how he would react.

665
00:43:11.797 --> 00:43:17.553
It seems William has been lost since
he learned the truth of his parentage.

666
00:43:18.596 --> 00:43:22.933
But. you and he share
a rather unique experience

667
00:43:23.934 --> 00:43:26.562
discovering that James Fraser
is your father.

668
00:43:28.022 --> 00:43:32.651
So that's why you invited me here.
not to paint a portrait of Amaranthus.

669
00:43:33.152 --> 00:43:34.612
You think I can help William.

670
00:43:34.695 --> 00:43:38.782
[hesitates] I do think that a portrait
of his grandchild and daughter-in-law

671
00:43:38.866 --> 00:43:42.578
will do my brother the world of good.
But... yes.

672
00:43:43.996 --> 00:43:46.582
If there's anyone who can talk
some sense into William

673
00:43:46.665 --> 00:43:50.210
about his present difficulties. it's you.

674
00:43:51.378 --> 00:43:54.048
You could've just told me the truth.
you know.

675
00:43:54.548 --> 00:43:56.050
I would have come anyway.

676
00:43:56.759 --> 00:44:00.220
I don't believe you've been
entirely truthful with me. either.

677
00:44:00.304 --> 00:44:05.059
Or should I ask precisely what errands
your husband has outside the city?

678
00:44:05.768 --> 00:44:10.439
Does it perhaps have something to do with
the Continental Army encampment there?

679
00:44:11.273 --> 00:44:12.107
[clears throat]

680
00:44:14.443 --> 00:44:18.364
I could have been more direct

681
00:44:18.447 --> 00:44:21.950
about my intentions for this visit.

682
00:44:22.034 --> 00:44:25.829
but I couldn't take the chance
you'd rebuff me now.

683
00:44:28.207 --> 00:44:33.879
If there's one trait that James Fraser
has successfully passed

684
00:44:33.962 --> 00:44:40.844
to all his children. it's stubbornness.
and it's exceedingly difficult

685
00:44:40.928 --> 00:44:43.847
to get you to do anything
you don't want to do.

686
00:44:44.598 --> 00:44:47.893
William... William is the same

687
00:44:51.980 --> 00:44:54.400
My late wife. Isobel. told me that William

688
00:44:54.483 --> 00:44:57.152
was lost once on his estate in Helwater.

689
00:44:58.570 --> 00:45:01.990
He was. um. three or so.

690
00:45:02.908 --> 00:45:06.286
He was wandering alone
in a fog on the fells.

691
00:45:09.998 --> 00:45:13.502
Sometimes I see that. Sometimes...

692
00:45:20.676 --> 00:45:21.969
Other things.

693
00:45:22.803 --> 00:45:25.055
You see those things when you're a parent.

694
00:45:27.683 --> 00:45:28.684
Yeah.

695
00:45:32.896 --> 00:45:34.982
I can't make any promises.

696
00:45:37.151 --> 00:45:39.111
But I will see what I can do.

697
00:45:40.904 --> 00:45:41.780
Thank you.

698
00:45:44.283 --> 00:45:45.701
Thank you. my dear. [kisses]

699
00:45:50.414 --> 00:45:51.915
- [baby crying]
- Shh. shh. shh.

700
00:46:20.611 --> 00:46:23.071
Jem and Mandy were a delight.

701
00:46:23.155 --> 00:46:25.741
Rodney and wee Claire can't wait
for their next...

702
00:46:25.824 --> 00:46:28.911
- What do they call it? A "sleepover"?
- [Claire chuckles]

703
00:46:30.120 --> 00:46:32.456
Well. I'm glad they weren't a nuisance.

704
00:46:32.539 --> 00:46:33.874
Never.

705
00:46:33.957 --> 00:46:35.250
Every child's a miracle.

706
00:46:38.212 --> 00:46:39.546
You all right. Rachel?

707
00:46:40.255 --> 00:46:41.089
Yes.

708
00:46:41.965 --> 00:46:45.093
Thee is right. Of course. Lizzie.
Every child is a miracle.

709
00:46:45.177 --> 00:46:48.889
Though. in Oggy's case. the miracle is how
long he can scream without drawing breath.

710
00:46:48.972 --> 00:46:51.016
Sometimes he sounds just like a catamount.

711
00:46:51.099 --> 00:46:52.559
We've all been there.

712
00:46:52.643 --> 00:46:55.437
- Mandy. look.
- [Mandy] Grandda! Grandda!

713
00:46:58.023 --> 00:46:58.982
[Jemmy] Come on!

714
00:46:59.066 --> 00:47:01.443
Come on! They're coming!
Quick. quick. quick!

715
00:47:01.527 --> 00:47:03.820
They're certainly happy
to see their grandda.

716
00:47:04.780 --> 00:47:06.490
Who's that with him?

717
00:47:06.573 --> 00:47:07.991
I have no idea.

718
00:47:12.538 --> 00:47:13.622
[Mandy] Buck!

719
00:47:13.830 --> 00:47:14.790
[chuckling]

720
00:47:15.123 --> 00:47:16.124
[Buck grunts]

721
00:47:16.833 --> 00:47:18.043
Children! Come here!

722
00:47:22.256 --> 00:47:23.090
How are you?

723
00:47:23.173 --> 00:47:25.717
- Granny. look. it's our cousin!
- [Mandy] Buck. It's Buck!

724
00:47:25.801 --> 00:47:29.471
Sassenach. may I introduce to you.
William Buccleigh MacKenzie.

725
00:47:30.472 --> 00:47:33.016
Claire Fraser. your reputation
precedes you.

726
00:47:33.100 --> 00:47:34.518
As does yours.

727
00:47:35.477 --> 00:47:38.105
You must have had
a very long journey indeed.

728
00:47:38.605 --> 00:47:40.566
Longer than I ken how to explain.

729
00:47:40.649 --> 00:47:43.777
I told him he's welcome to stay on
the Ridge as long as he likes.

730
00:47:43.860 --> 00:47:45.696
Of course. You're family.

731
00:47:46.405 --> 00:47:48.365
Come along. Come inside.

732
00:47:48.865 --> 00:47:52.160
- I'm sure you both must be starving.
- Aye.

733
00:47:52.244 --> 00:47:56.415
You don't happen to have any of those
peanut butter sandwiches. do you?

734
00:48:06.675 --> 00:48:08.302
What's troubling you. <i>mo chroi?</i>

735
00:48:09.970 --> 00:48:12.598
There was a massacre. Up north.

736
00:48:14.266 --> 00:48:16.685
A Mohawk leader. Joseph Brant.

737
00:48:16.768 --> 00:48:19.229
and a Loyalist captain.
led a raid on a Rebel town.

738
00:48:21.315 --> 00:48:22.482
I ken Joseph Brant.

739
00:48:25.569 --> 00:48:28.905
The Continentals retaliated
by sending an army after him.

740
00:48:35.579 --> 00:48:38.957
"Patriot Army marched along
the Susquehanna River.

741
00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:43.587
razing every Indian village
they could find.

742
00:48:43.670 --> 00:48:46.340
Forty villages were left in flames.

743
00:48:46.423 --> 00:48:49.051
and countless scalps were..."

744
00:48:50.927 --> 00:48:52.387
Christ.

745
00:48:52.471 --> 00:48:54.556
Is that not where Shadow Lake lies?

746
00:48:56.183 --> 00:48:57.517
Where thy former wife...

747
00:48:58.101 --> 00:48:58.935
Wahionhaweh.

748
00:49:01.188 --> 00:49:02.105
Aye.

749
00:49:04.274 --> 00:49:05.150
And thy son.

750
00:49:06.401 --> 00:49:07.903
[speaking other language]

751
00:49:09.279 --> 00:49:10.489
Swiftest of Lizards.

752
00:49:12.824 --> 00:49:13.825
Rachel.

753
00:49:17.579 --> 00:49:18.872
I must go north.

754
00:49:21.917 --> 00:49:24.086
I need to know what happened to them.

755
00:49:26.880 --> 00:49:28.215
Of course you must go.

756
00:49:32.928 --> 00:49:35.013
And Oggy and I will come with thee.

757
00:49:41.436 --> 00:49:42.646
[birds chirping]

758
00:49:45.857 --> 00:49:47.984
I'm going to miss this little catamount.

759
00:49:49.945 --> 00:49:52.864
Going to be so much bigger
by the time you return.

760
00:49:55.409 --> 00:49:58.578
Is there really nothing I can say
to convince you and Oggy to stay?

761
00:49:58.662 --> 00:50:00.914
I thank thee. Claire. but no.

762
00:50:01.248 --> 00:50:03.875
Would thee let thy husband
travel alone 700 miles

763
00:50:03.959 --> 00:50:05.335
to rescue his first wife?

764
00:50:06.086 --> 00:50:07.421
You make a good point.

765
00:50:14.928 --> 00:50:17.723
I pray that we find Emily
and her children safe.

766
00:50:18.849 --> 00:50:21.852
But when he sees them.
I want to be by his side...

767
00:50:23.687 --> 00:50:25.814
so he doesn't forget the life he has here.

768
00:50:29.860 --> 00:50:31.111
Does that make me wicked?

769
00:50:32.779 --> 00:50:34.614
No. Rachel.

770
00:50:36.283 --> 00:50:37.743
That makes you human.

771
00:50:39.244 --> 00:50:40.120
[Oggy cooing]

772
00:50:41.204 --> 00:50:42.080
Here.

773
00:50:49.379 --> 00:50:50.672
Come.

774
00:50:52.340 --> 00:50:55.051
Rachel says you mean to stop
in Philadelphia

775
00:50:55.135 --> 00:50:57.387
so she can go to a proper meeting?

776
00:50:57.471 --> 00:50:59.306
Aye. She's missed it.

777
00:51:00.515 --> 00:51:02.476
I'd like you to go to the brothel there.

778
00:51:02.559 --> 00:51:06.730
The one Frances lived wi' your sister.
Speak with some of the lasses.

779
00:51:06.813 --> 00:51:07.814
A brothel?

780
00:51:10.150 --> 00:51:12.402
It's not enough
I'm going to find my first wife?

781
00:51:12.486 --> 00:51:14.154
It's to do with Frances.

782
00:51:15.113 --> 00:51:18.325
Ask 'em about Jane.
Anything she said about her family.

783
00:51:19.117 --> 00:51:21.578
We'd like Frances to ken more about them.

784
00:51:22.829 --> 00:51:23.997
I'll find out what I can.

785
00:51:41.723 --> 00:51:42.682
I. uh...

786
00:51:44.184 --> 00:51:46.520
I must say one more thing
to you before you go.

787
00:51:52.234 --> 00:51:58.615
You ken the book Brianna brought back?
The one written by her other father?

788
00:51:58.698 --> 00:52:00.742
Aye. She told me...

789
00:52:01.868 --> 00:52:02.994
Frank Randall?

790
00:52:04.788 --> 00:52:06.790
It's about Scots in America.

791
00:52:07.874 --> 00:52:09.793
About what they...

792
00:52:10.919 --> 00:52:14.047
What we will do in the Revolution.

793
00:52:15.632 --> 00:52:18.051
There's mention of a battle
in the backcountry

794
00:52:18.134 --> 00:52:19.761
at a place called King's Mountain.

795
00:52:20.679 --> 00:52:21.930
I've heard of this place.

796
00:52:22.889 --> 00:52:24.558
Frank says I fight in it.

797
00:52:25.934 --> 00:52:27.018
When will it happen?

798
00:52:27.519 --> 00:52:28.562
October next.

799
00:52:29.729 --> 00:52:30.939
So he says.

800
00:52:31.022 --> 00:52:33.316
Claire thinks
he's bending the truth. but...

801
00:52:34.943 --> 00:52:37.153
I'm more and more convinced he's not.

802
00:52:45.704 --> 00:52:46.997
I'll be there with you. Uncle.

803
00:52:47.747 --> 00:52:49.833
There'll be time enough for me
to do what's needed

804
00:52:49.916 --> 00:52:51.877
in the north and make it home.

805
00:52:53.336 --> 00:52:55.589
Hey. dinna fash.

806
00:52:57.007 --> 00:53:00.844
My da may be gone. but I'll guard
your left in his stead.

807
00:53:04.890 --> 00:53:05.891
Thank you. lad.

808
00:53:06.933 --> 00:53:08.810
[somber music playing]

809
00:53:25.493 --> 00:53:27.579
May you be safe on your journey.

810
00:53:34.252 --> 00:53:35.253
[speaking Gaelic]

811
00:54:14.626 --> 00:54:15.835
[speaking French]

812
00:54:27.180 --> 00:54:29.057
- [in English] Afternoon.
- [Roger] Col. Marion.

813
00:54:29.557 --> 00:54:31.142
I'm Reverend Roger MacKenzie.

814
00:54:31.643 --> 00:54:34.854
I apologize for interrupting you. but...

815
00:54:34.938 --> 00:54:37.857
you're a difficult man to find.
and my request is urgent.

816
00:54:37.941 --> 00:54:39.609
You here to volunteer?

817
00:54:39.693 --> 00:54:41.569
The Continental Army isn't choosy.

818
00:54:41.653 --> 00:54:44.656
But I have to say.
the occasional minister we do get

819
00:54:44.739 --> 00:54:47.617
doesn't usually wear
his best clothes to fight in.

820
00:54:48.326 --> 00:54:49.202
No. sir.

821
00:54:49.911 --> 00:54:52.455
I've come to request your assistance.

822
00:54:55.333 --> 00:54:59.129
My father-in-law owns
ten thousand acres in North Carolina.

823
00:54:59.838 --> 00:55:03.008
A British major named Patrick Ferguson
has been stirring up trouble

824
00:55:03.091 --> 00:55:05.385
in the backcountry.
raising the Loyalist militias.

825
00:55:05.927 --> 00:55:09.472
And as we are Patriots. we've decided
to assemble a militia of our own.

826
00:55:10.640 --> 00:55:11.850
But we need weapons.

827
00:55:12.600 --> 00:55:15.061
I believe you've helped
arm others like this before.

828
00:55:15.145 --> 00:55:15.979
Mmm-hmm.

829
00:55:17.939 --> 00:55:18.857
I can pay you.

830
00:55:20.191 --> 00:55:22.485
I think we could possibly
reach an agreement.

831
00:55:23.945 --> 00:55:27.741
Well. I have a letter from
my father-in-law with the particulars.

832
00:55:35.665 --> 00:55:37.959
Your father-in-law
is General James Fraser?

833
00:55:39.127 --> 00:55:40.295
Aye.

834
00:55:40.378 --> 00:55:43.965
Fellow who abandoned his troops
at Monmouth to tend his wife.

835
00:55:45.050 --> 00:55:45.884
Aye.

836
00:55:48.470 --> 00:55:53.349
James Fraser is an honorable man. sir.
and a very brave soldier.

837
00:55:53.850 --> 00:55:56.186
The battle was already won
when his wife was shot.

838
00:55:56.269 --> 00:55:59.022
Is it true he signed
his letter of resignation

839
00:55:59.105 --> 00:56:00.732
on the back of a corporal in mud?

840
00:56:00.815 --> 00:56:04.069
Actually. he wrote it in his wife's blood.
but. aye.

841
00:56:06.029 --> 00:56:07.614
He didn't have a choice.

842
00:56:07.697 --> 00:56:11.076
She was wounded when General Lee
ordered him to leave her side. which...

843
00:56:11.159 --> 00:56:13.369
I'm sure the circumstances
were quite extraordinary.

844
00:56:13.453 --> 00:56:17.707
The fact remains that if it had not been
for Lee's trial and Lafayette's good word.

845
00:56:17.791 --> 00:56:20.710
Fraser would've been court-martialed
after Monmouth. perhaps even hanged.

846
00:56:21.336 --> 00:56:23.797
Sir. our people are in danger.

847
00:56:23.880 --> 00:56:26.216
Our circumstances here
are quite dire as well.

848
00:56:26.299 --> 00:56:28.551
We have precious few resources.

849
00:56:29.135 --> 00:56:31.638
even with the assistance
of our new French allies.

850
00:56:31.721 --> 00:56:33.681
I can't afford to give what I do have

851
00:56:33.765 --> 00:56:36.893
to someone who's already lost
the Continental Army's trust.

852
00:56:36.976 --> 00:56:40.021
Surely his years of service
and sacrifice to the cause...

853
00:56:40.105 --> 00:56:43.525
My answer is no.
Reverend MacKenzie. And it's final.

854
00:56:48.655 --> 00:56:52.075
- Then I'll take my leave. sir.
- That's not possible. I'm afraid.

855
00:56:52.867 --> 00:56:56.246
- I beg your pardon?
- We assault the city in a few days' time.

856
00:56:56.329 --> 00:56:59.958
General Lincoln has ordered sentries
to detain anyone leaving camp

857
00:57:00.041 --> 00:57:02.961
in an effort to prevent the deserters
from warning the British.

858
00:57:03.044 --> 00:57:04.254
You can't leave.

859
00:57:04.337 --> 00:57:06.965
I've come to ask for your help
in fighting the British.

860
00:57:07.048 --> 00:57:08.550
But surely you don't...

861
00:57:08.633 --> 00:57:10.760
think that I'm going
to leave here and assist them?

862
00:57:10.844 --> 00:57:13.346
I have my orders. Reverend MacKenzie.

863
00:57:13.429 --> 00:57:16.057
Sir. My wife is in the city.

864
00:57:17.058 --> 00:57:18.810
I promised I'd return.

865
00:57:20.645 --> 00:57:25.525
Every man here has made such a promise
to his wife. his mother. his son.

866
00:57:26.276 --> 00:57:28.528
Many will not live to honor them.

867
00:57:29.195 --> 00:57:30.280
You might.

868
00:57:30.947 --> 00:57:33.533
I can find a safe place
for you to wait out the battle.

869
00:57:33.616 --> 00:57:34.951
Unless you want to fight.

870
00:57:35.743 --> 00:57:37.412
I can give you a good rifle.

871
00:57:38.913 --> 00:57:39.831
No.

872
00:57:40.457 --> 00:57:41.374
Well...

873
00:57:43.293 --> 00:57:44.878
Stay here and wait then.

874
00:57:45.795 --> 00:57:48.173
Things go wrong. you can help bury us.

875
00:57:54.554 --> 00:57:55.763
Sir. wait.

876
00:58:01.269 --> 00:58:03.480
[hesitates] I'm no good with a rifle.

877
00:58:06.941 --> 00:58:09.569
But if you can give me a sword.
I'll fight with you.

878
00:58:12.238 --> 00:58:14.115
[patriotic music playing]

879
00:58:38.640 --> 00:58:40.642
[patriotic music continues]
